1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,850
A poppy field before sunrise, cold enough to show breath.

2
00:00:03,850 --> 00:00:17,359
The pods were scored the evening before and have wept their gum overnight; now a line of scrapers moves down the rows, lifting the grey beads off each pod with a curved iron before the dew burns away.

3
00:00:17,640 --> 00:00:33,232
At the edge of the field, where the rows meet the earthen bund, lies a girl on her side in the dirt: LEELA, sixteen, a printed kameez gone stiff with dew, one slipper on and one in the furrow beside her.

4
00:00:33,232 --> 00:00:44,599
An old woman scrapes the row nearest the body without looking at it, her lips going Ram Ram, Ram Ram, her iron not stopping; a boy works behind her.

5
00:00:44,880 --> 00:00:47,772
A CBN jeep pulls onto the field road.

6
00:00:47,772 --> 00:00:56,762
INSPECTOR RATAN SINGH PANWAR, fifties, heavy, a sweater under his uniform, gets out slowly with a hand on the door.

7
00:00:56,762 --> 00:01:01,999
Constable DEVA, twenty-four, follows a step behind and stays there.

8
00:01:02,280 --> 00:01:08,760
BHERULAL, the girl's father, comes across the field toward them but stops a few rows short of the body.

9
00:01:09,040 --> 00:01:18,080
You've come, sahib. At night... who knows why she went out. It was dark. She must have fallen. That's all. Just make out the papers, I'll sign.

10
00:01:18,360 --> 00:01:20,200
He still has not looked at her.

11
00:01:20,480 --> 00:01:21,785
Who saw her first?

12
00:01:21,785 --> 00:01:28,800
The scrapers. They came before dawn... she was lying here. I let no one touch her. She's just as she was.

13
00:01:29,080 --> 00:01:33,603
Ratan crouches beside the girl, slow, a hand on his knee.

14
00:01:33,603 --> 00:01:36,064
Deva photographs from the bund.

15
00:01:36,064 --> 00:01:39,079
Bherulal turns away, toward the field.

16
00:01:39,360 --> 00:01:40,832
She was engaged?

17
00:01:40,832 --> 00:01:46,800
Yes. The boy's people were coming in two days to fix the wedding date. If word spreads now...

18
00:01:47,080 --> 00:01:51,560
Ratan stands and looks at the scrapers still working the rows around the body.

19
00:01:51,840 --> 00:01:53,193
You've kept the work going.

20
00:01:53,193 --> 00:01:57,760
The gum doesn't wait, sahib. Should I... should I just stand here?

21
00:01:58,040 --> 00:02:01,080
Ratan looks at the field a moment, then turns to Deva.

22
00:02:01,360 --> 00:02:03,440
Clear the field. No scraping today.

23
00:02:03,720 --> 00:02:04,477
Deva goes.

24
00:02:04,477 --> 00:02:10,313
Down the field the scrapers stop and stand, holding their irons over the gum.

25
00:02:10,313 --> 00:02:12,360
Bherulal comes after Ratan.

26
00:02:12,640 --> 00:02:20,000
Don't stop it, sahib. Don't do this. If the crop doesn't come in... sahib, you know. I have nothing else...

27
00:02:20,280 --> 00:02:21,480
Ratan looks at him.

28
00:02:21,760 --> 00:02:30,637
Call two more men from the station. No — call four. And send the body to the district hospital for postmortem. We stay here today.

29
00:02:30,637 --> 00:02:36,240
Postmortem? Sahib, she died from a fall. Don't put her through more... just... let her be.

30
00:02:36,520 --> 00:02:38,120
He does not look at the father.

31
00:02:38,400 --> 00:02:42,480
It's the rule.

32
00:02:42,760 --> 00:02:54,680
Bherulal keeps at him — sahib, think once more — but Ratan has crouched back down beside the girl, and he stays there, and after a while the pleading stops on its own.

33
00:02:54,960 --> 00:03:00,328
A small room off the women's side, thin light through one barred window.

34
00:03:00,328 --> 00:03:06,218
The whole house smells of the gum, in the walls and in the dead girl's clothes.

35
00:03:06,218 --> 00:03:14,196
A string cot, a steel almirah, Leela's Class 10 guidebooks tied with string for the boards three weeks off.

36
00:03:14,196 --> 00:03:21,280
In the next room a woman's voice goes up — Oh my darling, oh my child — and the others take it up.

37
00:03:21,560 --> 00:03:29,560
SUGNA sits on the floor with her daughter's clothes in her lap, her shoulders shaking, a fold of the girl's clothes pressed to her mouth.

38
00:03:29,840 --> 00:03:31,666
RATAN fills the doorway.

39
00:03:31,666 --> 00:03:34,405
He steps in and goes to the almirah.

40
00:03:34,405 --> 00:03:36,080
Sugna's head comes up.

41
00:03:36,360 --> 00:03:39,240
What are you doing... these are my child's things.

42
00:03:39,520 --> 00:03:41,360
An AUNT comes in behind him.

43
00:03:41,640 --> 00:03:43,480
Sahib, step outside. This is the women's room.

44
00:03:43,760 --> 00:03:45,210
Ratan does not stop.

45
00:03:45,210 --> 00:04:02,320
He works the lid off a steel tin, and under a fold of cloth finds a smaller cloth knotted tight: a thin roll of tens and twenties and a fist of one-rupee coins, and a coaching-class handbill from Ratlam, soft at the folds from handling.

46
00:04:02,600 --> 00:04:08,280
Sugna has got to her feet and reached him, pulling at his arm, at the clothes in his hands.

47
00:04:08,560 --> 00:04:11,040
My darling... my child...

48
00:04:11,320 --> 00:04:17,797
Ratan looks at the handbill a moment, then folds the cloth back over the money and puts it in his pocket.

49
00:04:17,797 --> 00:04:23,720
The aunt comes and takes Sugna by the arm, and Sugna folds against her and lets herself be held.

50
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:25,920
He goes, out through the keening.

51
00:04:26,199 --> 00:04:35,991
A government room gone yellow at the edges — steel almirahs of files, a ceiling fan turning slow, a framed Gandhi over the door.

52
00:04:35,991 --> 00:04:42,646
SUPERINTENDENT MISHRA sits behind his desk with Leela's thin file open in front of him.

53
00:04:42,646 --> 00:04:43,640
Ratan stands.

54
00:04:43,640 --> 00:04:45,399
DEVA waits by the door.

55
00:04:45,679 --> 00:04:53,879
She fell in the field and died, and it's licensed land. The father's ready to sign. What's so much in this, Ratan?

56
00:04:53,879 --> 00:04:56,639
I've sent the body for postmortem.

57
00:04:56,919 --> 00:04:58,119
Mishra looks up.

58
00:04:58,399 --> 00:05:01,868
Who sent it?

59
00:05:01,868 --> 00:05:03,759
I did.

60
00:05:04,039 --> 00:05:08,599
Mishra sits back, the tiredness of a man who has settled a hundred of these.

61
00:05:08,879 --> 00:05:19,703
She's a village girl. There's a death in the house, it's a matter of honour. What will you get from cutting her open? Write the report, close it. I'll sign right now.

62
00:05:19,703 --> 00:05:26,804
The father wouldn't leave the crop, sahib. His child lay in front of him, and he was thinking about the harvest.

63
00:05:26,804 --> 00:05:39,359
Every father's in a hurry. Ratan. Whose licenses run this belt, who stands behind whom — who knows it better than you? Don't put your hand into someone's house for nothing.

64
00:05:39,639 --> 00:05:41,239
Ratan does not answer that.

65
00:05:41,519 --> 00:05:43,439
The report comes after the postmortem.

66
00:05:43,719 --> 00:05:47,319
Mishra holds his eye a moment, then drops it back to the file.

67
00:05:47,599 --> 00:05:49,999
Fine. Your report, your responsibility.

68
00:05:50,279 --> 00:05:51,683
Ratan turns to go.

69
00:05:51,683 --> 00:05:53,319
Deva follows him out.

70
00:05:53,599 --> 00:05:56,367
Ratan lowers himself into his chair.

71
00:05:56,367 --> 00:05:59,519
Deva hovers, the file still in his hands.

72
00:05:59,799 --> 00:06:04,681
Sahib... Mishra sahib isn't wrong. She must have slipped and fallen.

73
00:06:04,681 --> 00:06:09,990
Have you ever seen anyone slip and die in a poppy field?

74
00:06:09,990 --> 00:06:10,504
...No.

75
00:06:10,504 --> 00:06:11,959
Neither have I.

76
00:06:12,239 --> 00:06:12,768
A beat.

77
00:06:12,768 --> 00:06:14,959
Ratan does not go on with it.

78
00:06:15,239 --> 00:06:16,279
Order tea, Deva.

79
00:06:16,559 --> 00:06:24,737
The field at the end of the day, the lancing stopped on Ratan's order, the gum drying grey and useless on the pods.

80
00:06:24,737 --> 00:06:31,422
Ratan walks the bund where the body lay, Deva a step behind with a torch he does not need yet.

81
00:06:31,422 --> 00:06:33,413
At the field's edge, a well.

82
00:06:33,413 --> 00:06:37,039
The house two hundred metres off, its one light on.

83
00:06:37,319 --> 00:06:41,408
The house is there. She was found here, at this end of the field.

84
00:06:41,408 --> 00:06:44,599
What would she come to this end for, at night?

85
00:06:44,879 --> 00:06:48,959
Ratan looks past the well, to a footpath running off into the dark.

86
00:06:49,239 --> 00:06:50,895
Where does this path go?

87
00:06:50,895 --> 00:06:53,559
To the road. The bus stand's ahead — the Manasa one.

88
00:06:53,839 --> 00:06:56,879
Ratan stands a while where the path leaves the field.

89
00:06:57,159 --> 00:07:07,639
Who saw her last that night — at home, in the field, on the path. Ask everyone. Write down the names.

90
00:07:07,919 --> 00:07:13,600
An old NIGHT-WATCHMAN sits on a charpai outside a hut, a stick across his knees.

91
00:07:13,600 --> 00:07:15,731
Deva has brought him to Ratan.

92
00:07:15,731 --> 00:07:20,559
He is careful, an old man who has kept his job by not seeing things.

93
00:07:20,839 --> 00:07:22,713
Were you on watch that night?

94
00:07:22,713 --> 00:07:25,924
I was, sahib. My eyes shut for a bit in between.

95
00:07:25,924 --> 00:07:28,599
Did you see Leela? Bherulal's girl.

96
00:07:28,879 --> 00:07:31,359
The old man looks at the stick across his knees.

97
00:07:31,639 --> 00:07:37,181
...I saw her. Late at night. Alone, walking fast, toward the road.

98
00:07:37,181 --> 00:07:39,099
Crying? Frightened?

99
00:07:39,099 --> 00:07:48,689
It was so dark, sahib. She was just in a hurry. Whether anyone was behind her, I didn't see. I went back to sleep.

100
00:07:48,689 --> 00:07:50,927
Would anyone else have seen?

101
00:07:50,927 --> 00:07:58,599
I don't know. Sahib, don't put my name on any paper. I have to live here.

102
00:07:58,879 --> 00:08:06,484
A small farming household — a kitchen open to the courtyard, a hand-pump, the smell of frying onion.

103
00:08:06,484 --> 00:08:09,297
DEVA's mother, AMMA, works the dough.

104
00:08:09,297 --> 00:08:12,035
His father, BAPU, sits on a charpai.

105
00:08:12,035 --> 00:08:17,054
SUNITA, eighteen, Deva's sister, moves between them with the food.

106
00:08:17,054 --> 00:08:20,399
DEVA comes in from the day still in uniform.

107
00:08:20,679 --> 00:08:29,554
You're back. Wash up. Listen — Girdhari's son, Vijay. His family's proposing for Sunita.

108
00:08:29,554 --> 00:08:36,279
It's a good household. Two bigha of land, a license too. The boy's looking for work in the city.

109
00:08:36,559 --> 00:08:39,359
Sunita sets a bowl down and does not look up.

110
00:08:39,639 --> 00:08:46,896
Go meet them once. You're in uniform — your word carries weight.

111
00:08:46,896 --> 00:08:50,194
I'm caught up in a case right now, Amma.

112
00:08:50,194 --> 00:08:57,341
Cases will keep coming. The girl's age is slipping by. Well? You say something.

113
00:08:57,341 --> 00:08:59,319
Whatever you think is right.

114
00:08:59,599 --> 00:09:01,191
Deva looks at his sister.

115
00:09:01,191 --> 00:09:02,719
The day is still on him.

116
00:09:02,999 --> 00:09:04,801
Did anyone ask Sunita?

117
00:09:04,801 --> 00:09:10,439
What's there to ask, son? It's a good match. We wouldn't wish her ill.

118
00:09:10,719 --> 00:09:15,119
Sunita's eyes come up to Deva's for a second — and go back down to the food.

119
00:09:15,399 --> 00:09:18,534
So go and meet them. Day after tomorrow.

120
00:09:18,534 --> 00:09:20,679
...I'll see.

121
00:09:20,959 --> 00:09:27,199
Sunita carries the empty pot to the pump and works the handle, and the water covers whatever she does not say.

122
00:09:27,479 --> 00:09:33,430
The house asleep, one low bulb still on in the corner where SUNITA has her bedding.

123
00:09:33,430 --> 00:09:39,595
She sits up with a school notebook open in her lap and a pen in her hand, not writing.

124
00:09:39,595 --> 00:09:46,118
From the parents' room, the murmur of the match goes on — Girdhari's boy, two bigha, a license.

125
00:09:46,118 --> 00:09:49,559
She listens to it the way you listen to weather.

126
00:09:49,839 --> 00:09:52,639
Deva comes in for water, sees her awake.

127
00:09:52,919 --> 00:09:54,428
Go to sleep.

128
00:09:54,428 --> 00:10:01,468
Will you go to meet them? Day after? Them?

129
00:10:01,468 --> 00:10:03,479
I'll see.

130
00:10:03,759 --> 00:10:07,519
Sunita closes the notebook and lies down, her face to the wall.

131
00:10:07,799 --> 00:10:12,519
Leave it. Everything's fine.

132
00:10:12,799 --> 00:10:16,079
Deva stands with the glass in his hand and does not drink it.

133
00:10:16,359 --> 00:10:21,416
A line of licensed growers waits with their season's gum in steel lotas.

134
00:10:21,416 --> 00:10:31,178
At the scale sits KHARE, the measurement officer, fifty and neat, weighing a farmer's lump of latex and writing the figure into a register.

135
00:10:31,178 --> 00:10:34,759
A FARMER watches the needle like his life is on it.

136
00:10:35,039 --> 00:10:38,479
It's short. Less than last time, even. Mind it next time.

137
00:10:38,759 --> 00:10:42,302
The farmer takes his receipt and goes, not arguing.

138
00:10:42,302 --> 00:10:44,386
Ratan has come up at the side.

139
00:10:44,386 --> 00:10:47,719
Khare sees him, and a practised warmth comes on.

140
00:10:47,999 --> 00:10:50,645
Ah, Ratan sahib. I heard about Bherulal's girl.

141
00:10:50,645 --> 00:10:52,959
Does Bherulal give full weight here?

142
00:10:53,239 --> 00:10:55,159
The pen stops for half a second.

143
00:10:55,439 --> 00:11:01,052
The girl fell and died, sahib. What's Bherulal's license got to do with that?

144
00:11:01,052 --> 00:11:02,479
I'm just asking.

145
00:11:02,759 --> 00:11:07,159
Khare leans in, the practised warmth gone, his voice dropped.

146
00:11:07,439 --> 00:11:16,352
Ratan. Bherulal's in debt, and whose debt it is, you know too. Everyone's accounts are running even here. Don't stick your leg in the middle.

147
00:11:16,352 --> 00:11:17,759
A girl is dead, Khare.

148
00:11:18,039 --> 00:11:21,799
Khare goes back to his register and the next man's lota.

149
00:11:22,079 --> 00:11:23,679
Girls keep dying around here.

150
00:11:23,959 --> 00:11:30,793
A roadside stall, a kettle, men on a bench with glasses of tea, the bazaar behind.

151
00:11:30,793 --> 00:11:32,959
The talk is the dead girl.

152
00:11:32,959 --> 00:11:35,959
They do not lower their voices much.

153
00:11:36,239 --> 00:11:40,120
Heard about it? Bherulal's girl. At night, in the field.

154
00:11:40,120 --> 00:11:47,268
What was she doing in the field at night — nobody asks that. Girls these days.

155
00:11:47,268 --> 00:11:50,944
She was engaged, wasn't she? Into a good family?

156
00:11:50,944 --> 00:11:53,599
She was. God's will.

157
00:11:53,879 --> 00:11:56,679
A third man, older, has been quiet.

158
00:11:56,959 --> 00:12:01,091
The CBN man's nosing around. Had a postmortem done.

159
00:12:01,091 --> 00:12:06,719
Will he let it go? These people have reach right to the top. Ratan sahib is sensible. He'll get it closed.

160
00:12:06,999 --> 00:12:08,599
They drink their tea.

161
00:12:08,879 --> 00:12:11,237
Tiles, a steel table, a drain.

162
00:12:11,237 --> 00:12:13,359
Leela's body under a sheet.

163
00:12:13,359 --> 00:12:20,038
The medical officer, DOCTOR VERMA, fills a form standing up, wanting to be elsewhere.

164
00:12:20,038 --> 00:12:22,159
Ratan and Deva at the door.

165
00:12:22,439 --> 00:12:27,884
Head injury, from the fall. It's clear. I'm writing 'brought dead'.

166
00:12:27,884 --> 00:12:28,935
Did you send the viscera?

167
00:12:28,935 --> 00:12:30,941
What for? The injury's right there.

168
00:12:30,941 --> 00:12:33,616
Lungs, stomach, blood — send all of it.

169
00:12:33,616 --> 00:12:43,550
Inspector, four bodies come here every day. If I sent everyone's viscera the lab would collapse. Has something been said from above?

170
00:12:43,550 --> 00:12:48,039
If it had, the word would be to stop it, not to send it.

171
00:12:48,319 --> 00:12:52,457
Verma looks at him, then at the small shape under the sheet.

172
00:12:52,457 --> 00:12:58,319
He folds the sheet back from her face and leans in, and something stops him a moment.

173
00:12:58,599 --> 00:13:08,494
The injury is from a fall, but... all right, I'll send it. The report will take a week to ten days.

174
00:13:08,494 --> 00:13:09,959
Get it done quickly.

175
00:13:10,239 --> 00:13:13,240
Another grower's plot, another lancing crew.

176
00:13:13,240 --> 00:13:18,764
The grower, HUKMA, walks Ratan along his rows, easy, the two of them old at this.

177
00:13:18,764 --> 00:13:31,039
At the end of the row Hukma folds a few notes into Ratan's hand the way you'd pass a relative something for the children, and Ratan takes them the way you take it, without looking.

178
00:13:31,319 --> 00:13:36,058
If the weighing runs a little off this time... well, you're there, sahib.

179
00:13:36,058 --> 00:13:36,890
We'll see to it.

180
00:13:36,890 --> 00:13:39,799
That Bherulal business... it'll all be set right, won't it?

181
00:13:40,079 --> 00:13:41,839
Ratan does not answer that.

182
00:13:41,839 --> 00:13:49,919
He pockets the notes and walks back to the jeep, and for a second he stands at the door with his hand on it, not getting in.

183
00:13:50,199 --> 00:13:53,332
The jeep pulled over on an empty country road.

184
00:13:53,332 --> 00:14:01,979
Ratan stands at the edge of a field that is not part of his case — a good plot, well worked, someone's gum drying on the racks.

185
00:14:01,979 --> 00:14:06,405
He looks at it the way a man looks at a house he used to live in.

186
00:14:06,405 --> 00:14:11,239
A YOUNG FARMER slows his motorcycle, sees the uniform, folds his hands.

187
00:14:11,519 --> 00:14:14,293
Ram Ram, sahib.

188
00:14:14,293 --> 00:14:15,999
Ram Ram.

189
00:14:16,279 --> 00:14:21,879
Ratan looks at the field a moment longer, then gets back in the jeep, and it goes dark behind him.

190
00:14:22,159 --> 00:14:24,788
The condolence crowd has thinned.

191
00:14:24,788 --> 00:14:32,434
DAULATRAM, fifty-five, the groom's uncle, prosperous and unhurried, sits where the mourners sat.

192
00:14:32,434 --> 00:14:37,133
Behind him stands PRATAP, forty, the groom, saying nothing.

193
00:14:37,133 --> 00:14:40,239
Bherulal receives them with both hands.

194
00:14:40,519 --> 00:14:46,915
Very bad business, Bherulal. Who can turn aside what's fated? But we must speak of what's ahead too.

195
00:14:46,915 --> 00:14:51,645
Yes, of course. The bond between us will hold, Daulatram-ji.

196
00:14:51,645 --> 00:14:58,040
The girl is gone. And the accounts that stood — the debt, the land — those were tied to the match.

197
00:14:58,040 --> 00:15:01,719
The debt... I'll repay it. Just a little time.

198
00:15:01,999 --> 00:15:03,919
Daulatram lets that sit.

199
00:15:03,919 --> 00:15:04,959
Then, easily:

200
00:15:05,239 --> 00:15:06,999
How old is your younger one?

201
00:15:07,279 --> 00:15:09,930
Something goes across Bherulal's face.

202
00:15:09,930 --> 00:15:12,719
His elder girl is not yet in the ground.

203
00:15:12,999 --> 00:15:13,767
...Twelve.

204
00:15:13,767 --> 00:15:16,839
When she's older, we'll talk. Keep the accounts square.

205
00:15:17,119 --> 00:15:23,937
Pratap looks at the house a moment — the dead girl's house — with flat eyes, and follows his uncle out.

206
00:15:23,937 --> 00:15:26,319
Bherulal stands where they left him.

207
00:15:26,599 --> 00:15:27,784
The women's side.

208
00:15:27,784 --> 00:15:35,799
An older relative, the AUNT, sorts through Leela's things into a cloth bundle to be given away, the way it is done.

209
00:15:35,799 --> 00:15:41,027
Bherulal's younger daughter, NANHI, twelve, sits against the wall watching.

210
00:15:41,027 --> 00:15:44,999
SUGNA is on the floor, not helping, her hands in her lap.

211
00:15:45,279 --> 00:15:49,679
The aunt holds up a kameez, decides, folds it into the bundle.

212
00:15:49,959 --> 00:15:53,639
What will you do keeping these? They'll serve someone in need.

213
00:15:53,919 --> 00:15:55,216
Sugna says nothing.

214
00:15:55,216 --> 00:15:58,559
Nanhi watches a green dupatta go into the bundle.

215
00:15:58,839 --> 00:16:00,069
That's my sister's.

216
00:16:00,069 --> 00:16:02,439
Yes, child. Your sister isn't here anymore.

217
00:16:02,719 --> 00:16:04,430
Nanhi looks at her mother.

218
00:16:04,430 --> 00:16:08,773
Sugna does not look back at her, or at the bundle, or at anything.

219
00:16:08,773 --> 00:16:13,839
Her hands stay folded in her lap as the last of the girl goes into the cloth.

220
00:16:14,119 --> 00:16:20,545
Mishra is on the phone, listening far more than he speaks, his face gone careful.

221
00:16:20,545 --> 00:16:21,814
He puts it down.

222
00:16:21,814 --> 00:16:23,479
Ratan is at the door.

223
00:16:23,759 --> 00:16:27,377
Ratan. Come in. A call just came. From above.

224
00:16:27,377 --> 00:16:27,964
From whom?

225
00:16:27,964 --> 00:16:33,244
They were asking why the Bherulal matter still isn't closed.

226
00:16:33,244 --> 00:16:35,199
Let the report come, sahib.

227
00:16:35,479 --> 00:16:40,679
Mishra comes around the desk, and what is in his voice now is almost kindness.

228
00:16:40,959 --> 00:16:56,066
Twenty-five years you've served. Two years left, your pension in sight. For one dead girl you'll take on the men at the top? They'll ruin you in a single stroke. Do you understand?

229
00:16:56,066 --> 00:16:57,126
I understand.

230
00:16:57,126 --> 00:16:58,274
Then close it.

231
00:16:58,274 --> 00:16:59,599
Let the report come.

232
00:16:59,879 --> 00:17:05,719
Mishra looks at him a long moment, the way you look at a man walking into something, and lets him go.

233
00:17:05,999 --> 00:17:10,587
A narrow lane, a wall, the back of the government school.

234
00:17:10,587 --> 00:17:15,578
RESHMA, sixteen, in school uniform, walking fast with her bag.

235
00:17:15,578 --> 00:17:17,671
Ratan falls in beside her.

236
00:17:17,671 --> 00:17:19,119
She does not stop.

237
00:17:19,399 --> 00:17:21,829
You were Leela's friend. Reshma.

238
00:17:21,829 --> 00:17:23,719
I don't know anything, sahib.

239
00:17:23,999 --> 00:17:27,519
He holds out the Ratlam handbill, folded soft.

240
00:17:27,799 --> 00:17:38,199
This was with her. A coaching slip, from Ratlam. I haven't come to trap her, child. I've come to learn what happened.

241
00:17:38,479 --> 00:17:39,402
Reshma slows.

242
00:17:39,402 --> 00:17:42,239
She looks back down the empty lane once.

243
00:17:42,519 --> 00:17:49,806
She wanted to study. Further. Go to Ratlam. She was saving money, in secret.

244
00:17:49,806 --> 00:17:51,131
In secret from whom?

245
00:17:51,131 --> 00:18:04,599
From her family. Her marriage was fixed — to that man who was much older. Leela used to say: I won't go there. I'll run, I'll study.

246
00:18:04,879 --> 00:18:06,067
The lane is quiet.

247
00:18:06,067 --> 00:18:11,279
Reshma's eyes fill, and she wipes them with the back of her wrist, angry at it.

248
00:18:11,559 --> 00:18:15,526
Sahib, don't tell anyone my name. I have to go.

249
00:18:15,526 --> 00:18:18,199
Did anyone help her? To run?

250
00:18:18,479 --> 00:18:24,879
But she has already pulled her bag up and gone, fast, the way you go when you have said one word too many.

251
00:18:25,159 --> 00:18:29,680
The jeep on a dark road, the fields black on both sides.

252
00:18:29,680 --> 00:18:30,649
Deva drives.

253
00:18:30,649 --> 00:18:34,039
Ratan beside him, the day behind his eyes.

254
00:18:34,319 --> 00:18:39,593
She was running. From the very man she was promised to. Forty years old.

255
00:18:39,593 --> 00:18:41,839
Forty. And Leela sixteen.

256
00:18:42,119 --> 00:18:43,159
They drive a while.

257
00:18:43,439 --> 00:18:49,839
Sahib... there's talk for my sister too. Good boy, land, a license. I'm to go meet them, day after tomorrow.

258
00:18:49,839 --> 00:18:51,039
Did your sister say yes?

259
00:18:51,319 --> 00:18:55,719
Deva opens his mouth to answer, and finds he does not have one.

260
00:18:55,999 --> 00:18:56,879
...I don't know.

261
00:18:57,159 --> 00:19:02,519
Ratan looks out at the dark fields and does not say anything, and lets the boy sit with it.

262
00:19:02,799 --> 00:19:04,959
Morning, the family at tea.

263
00:19:04,959 --> 00:19:09,999
BAPU is dressed to go — the visit to the boy's family is today.

264
00:19:09,999 --> 00:19:12,799
AMMA presses a clean shirt on Deva.

265
00:19:12,799 --> 00:19:14,719
Sunita pours, eyes down.

266
00:19:14,999 --> 00:19:19,319
Come on, Deva, it's getting late. Girdhari will be waiting.

267
00:19:19,599 --> 00:19:21,439
Deva does not get up.

268
00:19:21,719 --> 00:19:24,199
Bapu. Did we ask her? Sunita?

269
00:19:24,479 --> 00:19:26,345
The room stops a little.

270
00:19:26,345 --> 00:19:27,199
Bapu turns.

271
00:19:27,479 --> 00:19:29,113
What kind of talk is this?

272
00:19:29,113 --> 00:19:32,119
We just ask. Once. You say it. Do you want to go?

273
00:19:32,399 --> 00:19:34,562
Sunita's hand stays on the kettle.

274
00:19:34,562 --> 00:19:39,839
The whole house waits on her, and for a moment it is not certain what she will say.

275
00:19:40,119 --> 00:19:41,183
A small house.

276
00:19:41,183 --> 00:19:43,463
Ratan eats alone at the table.

277
00:19:43,463 --> 00:19:49,999
His wife, KANTA, clears a pot in the back, the two of them long past needing to speak.

278
00:19:49,999 --> 00:19:50,607
A knock.

279
00:19:50,607 --> 00:19:56,839
At the door, A MAN — pressed shirt, calm, the kind that is never quite introduced.

280
00:19:57,119 --> 00:20:00,479
Ratan sahib. Forgive the late hour. Two minutes.

281
00:20:00,759 --> 00:20:06,199
He steps in only as far as he needs to, and sets a thick envelope on the edge of the table.

282
00:20:06,479 --> 00:20:13,999
The Bherulal matter. There's a wish from above that it close quickly. An accident, that's all. And this — for your trouble.

283
00:20:14,279 --> 00:20:16,209
Ratan looks at the envelope.

284
00:20:16,209 --> 00:20:18,414
He has taken a hundred of these.

285
00:20:18,414 --> 00:20:21,239
Kanta, in the back, does not turn around.

286
00:20:21,519 --> 00:20:23,254
Whose wish?

287
00:20:23,254 --> 00:20:25,999
You're a sensible man.

288
00:20:26,279 --> 00:20:28,187
The envelope sits between them.

289
00:20:28,187 --> 00:20:30,833
It would be the easiest thing in the world.

290
00:20:30,833 --> 00:20:33,479
Then Ratan slides it back across the table.

291
00:20:33,759 --> 00:20:34,399
Not this time.

292
00:20:34,679 --> 00:20:36,039
The smile goes.

293
00:20:36,319 --> 00:20:39,776
Think it over, sahib. This road won't be good for you.

294
00:20:39,776 --> 00:20:40,879
It's gotten very late.

295
00:20:41,159 --> 00:20:43,963
The man takes his envelope and goes.

296
00:20:43,963 --> 00:20:44,820
Ratan sits.

297
00:20:44,820 --> 00:20:49,959
After a while Kanta speaks from the back, not unkind, not hopeful.

298
00:20:50,239 --> 00:20:52,559
What fight are you picking at this age?

299
00:20:52,839 --> 00:20:54,754
Ratan does not answer her.

300
00:20:54,754 --> 00:20:57,479
He looks at the door the man left by.

301
00:20:57,759 --> 00:20:59,380
Late, the office empty.

302
00:20:59,380 --> 00:21:03,185
Ratan sits with Leela's thin file open under the lamp.

303
00:21:03,185 --> 00:21:10,935
Her school photo is clipped to the corner — a girl grinning crooked at a camera, a board exam three weeks off.

304
00:21:10,935 --> 00:21:13,119
He looks at it for a long time.

305
00:21:13,399 --> 00:21:14,818
The mourners are gone.

306
00:21:14,818 --> 00:21:15,979
The house is dark.

307
00:21:15,979 --> 00:21:24,493
SUGNA sits alone against the wall where the women keened all day, her daughter's folded clothes in her lap, her hands still on them.

308
00:21:24,493 --> 00:21:30,039
The camera holds on her, on her hands on the folded clothes, and does not move either.
